2. VAR(1)-model

Estimate a VAR(1)-model for the market.

a) Estimate the parameters (include them in the report) and check whether the model is stable or not

(this check should also be detailed in the report).

Method:

  • Computed log-returns for all variables and selected the stock-related columns for the VAR(1) analysis.
  • Defined lagged values of the log-returns as variables and built the regression matrix with ones in the first column.
  • Estimated the VAR(1) parameters for each stock using the normal equation.
  • Stored the estimated intercepts and coefficients in a parameter table.
  • Formed the coefficient matrix (A) from lagged parameters and calculated its eigenvalues.
  • Checked model stability by confirming that all eigenvalues lie inside the unit circle (absolute value < 1).
In[]:
log_returns = np.log(df).diff().dropna()
stock_cols = list(range(0, 15))  # columns 2 to 11

log_returns_stocks = log_returns.iloc[:, stock_cols]
T, K = log_returns_stocks.shape

M = np.hstack([np.ones((T-1, 1)),log_returns_stocks.values[:-1, :]])
parameters = []
for k in range(K):
    Y_k = log_returns_stocks.values[1:, k]
    a_k = np.linalg.inv(M.T @ M) @ M.T @ Y_k #normalekvationen
    parameters.append(a_k)

tickers = ["BA", "CAT", "KO", "DIS", "JPM", "MMM", "MSFT", "PFE", "WMT", "XOM", "Y05", "Y10", "Y15", "Y20", "Y30"]

param_matrix = np.vstack(parameters)  #  (K, K+1)
row_labels = tickers
col_labels = ["A0"] + [f"A_{t}" for t in tickers]

param_df = pd.DataFrame(param_matrix, index=row_labels, columns=col_labels)

A = np.vstack([a_k[1:] for a_k in parameters])  #  (K, K)

eigvals = np.linalg.eigvals(A)

Method:

    Yhat_k = M @ parameters[k]  # Predicted values
    residuals_matrix[:, k] = Y_k - Yhat_k #residuals

c) Simulate 5000 scenarios with 480 weekly time steps for all assets and plot the price (or interest rate) percentiles (5%, 10%, 25%, 50%, 75%, 90%, 95%) for the stocks Caterpillar and Walmart and the 5- and 30-year interest rates. A total of four plots. Also list these percentiles, for the time periods 240 and 480, in two tables with the percentiles in the horizontal direction and the stocks and interest rates in the vertical direction.

Method:

  • Estimated the residual covariance of the VAR(1) and obtained a Cholesky factor to generate correlated shocks.
  • Initialized the VAR state with the last observed weekly log-returns and simulated 5,000 scenarios over 480 weeks by iterating the VAR(1) recursion.
  • Cumulated simulated log-returns to get cumulative log-returns, then transformed back to price/level paths using the last observed values as starting points.
  • For each of CAT, WMT, Y05, and Y30, computed time-series percentiles across scenarios and plotted these percentile curves.
  • Formed two tables with percentiles in columns and the four assets in rows.
In[]:
cov_matrix = np.cov(residuals_matrix, rowvar=False)
C = np.linalg.cholesky(cov_matrix) #lower triangualr matrix

A0 = param_matrix[:, 0]

steps = 480        # horizon (weeks)
n = 5000       # scenarios

# Start state for the VAR in returns: last observed return vector (1xK)
y_last = log_returns_stocks.values[-1]  # shape (K,)

# paths of returns: (5000, 480, 10)
ret_paths = np.zeros((n, steps, K))
y_prev = np.tile(y_last, (n, 1))  # (5000,10)

for t in range(steps):
    Z = np.random.randn(n, K)
    eps = Z @ C.T
    y_t = A0 + y_prev @ A.T + eps
    ret_paths[:, t, :] = y_t
    y_prev = y_t

P0 = df.iloc[-1, stock_cols].values

# cumulative log-returns over time
cum_log_ret = np.cumsum(ret_paths, axis=1)        # (5000,480,10)

price_paths_VAR = np.exp(cum_log_ret) * P0

#Percentile plots for CAT and WMT
assets_to_plot = ["CAT", "WMT", "Y05", "Y30"]
percentiles = [5, 10, 25, 50, 75, 90, 95]
indices_assets = [tickers.index(asset) for asset in assets_to_plot]

for asset in assets_to_plot:
    idx = tickers.index(asset)
    q = np.percentile(price_paths_VAR[:, :, idx], q=percentiles, axis=0)  # shape: (len(percentiles), steps)
    plot_df = pd.DataFrame(q.T, columns=[f"{p}%" for p in percentiles])

    plot_df.plot(
        title=f"{asset} Price Percentiles (S={n}, H={steps})",
        figsize=(9, 5),
        legend=True
    )
    plt.xlabel("Weeks ahead")
    plt.ylabel("Price")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

perc_240_VAR = np.percentile(price_paths_VAR[:, 240 - 1, indices_assets], q=percentiles, axis=0).T
perc_480_VAR = np.percentile(price_paths_VAR[:, 480 - 1, indices_assets], q=percentiles, axis=0).T

df_240_VAR = pd.DataFrame(perc_240_VAR, columns=[f"{p}%" for p in percentiles], index=assets_to_plot)
df_480_VAR = pd.DataFrame(perc_480_VAR, columns=[f"{p}%" for p in percentiles], index=assets_to_plot)

4. VAR(1)-DCC-model

Estimate a VAR(1)-DCC-model for the market

a) Plot the ACF, for lags 1 to 50, for the (weekly) residuals and square residuals of the VAR-model, for Caterpillar and the 5-year interest rate.

Method:

  • Defined a custom function to compute the autocorrelation function (ACF) for a given time series up to a specified number of lags.
  • Applied the ACF function to the VAR(1) residuals and squared residuals of Caterpillar (CAT) and the 5-year interest rate (Y05) to check for serial correlation and volatility clustering.
  • Calculated ACF values for 50 weekly lags for both residuals and squared residuals.
  • Established 95% confidence intervals to visually assess the statistical significance of the correlations.
In[]:
def compute_acf(data, lag): #lecture2 slide 4,5,6
  y = np.asarray(data)
  T = len(y)
  y_bar = np.sum(y)/T
  C0 = np.sum((y - y_bar)**2) / T
  Ck = np.zeros(lag)
  for k in range(1, lag + 1):
    total = 0.0
    for t in range(0,T-k):
      total = total + (y[t] - y_bar) * (y[t+k] - y_bar)
    Ck[k-1] = total/T
  rho = Ck/C0
  return C0, Ck, rho

lag = 50

#CAT
C0_returns, Ck_returns, residuals_CAT = compute_acf(residuals_matrix[:, 1], lag)
C0_sq_returns, Ck_sq_returns, squared_residuals_CAT = compute_acf(residuals_matrix[:, 1]**2, lag)

#Y05

b) Estimate the DCC-model and include the DCC-parameters in the report: delta, gamma, the R-matrix and the GARCH(1,1)-parameters as a 15*3-matrix

Method:

  • Estimated univariate GARCH(1,1) models for each assets VAR(1) residuals using maximum likelihood estimation.
  • Extracted and stored the estimated parameters (omega, alpha, beta) in a 153 matrix for all assets.
  • Standardized the residuals using the estimated conditional volatilities.
  • Computed the unconditional correlation matrix (R) from standardized residuals.
  • Estimated the DCC parameters (delta and gamma) via grid search, maximizing the log-likelihood under the DCC specification while ensuring delta + gamma < 1 for stationarity.
In[]:
# GARCH likelihood from labb1
def garch_likelihood(params, returns):
    omega, alpha, beta = params
    T = len(returns)
    sigma2 = np.zeros(T)
    sigma2[0] = np.var(returns)
    for t in range(1, T):
        sigma2[t] = omega + alpha * returns[t-1]**2 + beta * sigma2[t-1]
    garch_likelihood.last_sigma2 = sigma2[-1]
    loglik = -0.5 * np.sum(np.log(sigma2) + returns**2 / sigma2)
    return -loglik  # minimize negative log-likelihood

init_params = [0.002, 0.06, 0.9]
bounds = [(1e-8, None), (0, 1), (0, 1)]
garch_params = []
sigmas = np.zeros_like(residuals_matrix)
for k in range(K):
    returns_k = residuals_matrix[:, k]
    res = minimize(garch_likelihood, init_params, args=(returns_k,), bounds=bounds)
    omega, alpha, beta = res.x
    garch_params.append([omega, alpha, beta])
    # Recompute sigma for the series
    T = len(returns_k)
    sigma2 = np.zeros(T)
    sigma2[0] = np.var(returns_k)
    for t in range(1, T):
        sigma2[t] = omega + alpha * returns_k[t-1]**2 + beta * sigma2[t-1]
    sigmas[:, k] = np.sqrt(sigma2)
garch_param_df = pd.DataFrame(garch_params, index=tickers, columns=['omega', 'alpha', 'beta'])
print("\nGARCH(1,1) Parameters:\n", garch_param_df)

# Standardize residuals
z = residuals_matrix / sigmas

# Estimate unconditional correlation R
S = np.cov(z, rowvar=False)
R = S / np.sqrt(np.outer(np.diag(S), np.diag(S)))
print("\nUnconditional R-matrix:\n", np.round(R, 3))

# Estimate DCC parameters (delta, gamma) by "simple "grid searchh
def dcc_loglik(z, R, delta, gamma):
    T, N = z.shape
    Q = R.copy()
    loglik = 0
    for t in range(T):
        Q = (1 - delta - gamma) * R + delta * np.outer(z[t], z[t]) + gamma * Q
        diag_sqrt = np.sqrt(np.diag(Q))
        R_t = Q / np.outer(diag_sqrt, diag_sqrt)
        invR = np.linalg.inv(R_t)
        sign, logdet = np.linalg.slogdet(R_t)
        loglik += -0.5 * (logdet + z[t].T @ invR @ z[t])
    return -loglik  # minimize

delta_range = np.linspace(0.01, 0.98, 10)
gamma_range = np.linspace(0.01, 0.98, 10)
best_ll = np.inf
best_delta = best_gamma = None
for delta in delta_range:
    for gamma in gamma_range:
        if delta + gamma < 1:
            ll = dcc_loglik(z, R, delta, gamma)
            if ll < best_ll:
                best_ll = ll
                best_delta, best_gamma = delta, gamma
print(f"\nDCC parameters: delta={best_delta:.4f}, gamma={best_gamma:.4f}")

# Simulate VAR(1)-DCC scenarios
n = 5000
steps = 480

y_last = log_returns.values[-1]
D_diag = np.std(residuals_matrix, axis=0)
D = np.diag(D_diag)
P0 = df.iloc[-1, :].values

def VAR_DCC(A0, A, y_last, D, R, delta, gamma, steps, n, P0):
    K = len(A0)
    ret_paths = np.zeros((n, steps, K))
    Q = np.tile(R, (n, 1, 1))  # (n, K, K)
    z_prev = np.zeros((n, K))
    y_prev = np.tile(y_last, (n, 1))
    for t in range(steps):
        outer_zz = z_prev[:, :, None] * z_prev[:, None, :]
        Q = (1 - delta - gamma) * R + delta * outer_zz + gamma * Q
        diag_sqrt = np.sqrt(np.diagonal(Q, axis1=1, axis2=2))
        diag_sqrt[diag_sqrt == 0] = 1e-8
        R_t = Q / (diag_sqrt[:, :, None] * diag_sqrt[:, None, :])
        Sigma_t = D @ R_t @ D
        eps = np.array([np.random.multivariate_normal(np.zeros(K), Sigma_t[i]) for i in range(n)])
        y_t = A0 + y_prev @ A.T + eps
        ret_paths[:, t, :] = y_t
        y_prev = y_t
        z_prev = eps / D_diag
    cum_log_ret = np.cumsum(ret_paths, axis=1)
    price_paths = np.exp(cum_log_ret) * P0
    return ret_paths, price_paths

ret_paths_dcc, price_paths_dcc = VAR_DCC(A0, A, y_last, D, R, best_delta, best_gamma, steps, n, P0)

What does a) tell you?

The ACF plots of the residuals and squared residuals for Caterpillar (CAT) and the 5-year interest rate (Y05) indicate that the model has not fully captured all the serial dependence and volatility dynamics in the data. ages = range(20,91)

mu_men_array_cut = mu_men_series.values[0:71]
mu_women_array_cut = mu_women_series.values[0:71]

mu_men_array = mu_men_series.values
mu_women_array = mu_women_series.values
ages_array = np.array(ages)


# Initial guess for gamma
gamma_initial = float(0.1)

def gamma_optim(gamma, mu_values, ages):
    N = len(ages)
    f1_gamma = np.sum(np.exp(gamma * ages))
    f2_gamma = np.sum(np.exp(2 * gamma * ages))
    g_gamma = np.sum(mu_values * np.exp(gamma * ages))
    m = np.sum(mu_values)

    # Solve for alpha and beta
    alpha = ((m * f2_gamma) - (g_gamma * f1_gamma)) / ((N * f2_gamma) - (f1_gamma ** 2))
    beta = ((m * f1_gamma) - (N * g_gamma)) / ((f1_gamma ** 2 ) - (N * f2_gamma))

    #  sum of squared errors
    predicted_mu = alpha + beta * np.exp(gamma * ages)
    diff_errors = predicted_mu - mu_values
    sse = np.sum((diff_errors)**2)
    return sse

def fit_makeham(ages, mu_values, gamma_initial):
    N = len(ages)
    # Optimize for gamma
    result = minimize(gamma_optim, gamma_initial, args=(mu_values, ages))
    gamma = result.x[0]

    # Calculate alpha and beta with optimized gamma
    f1_gamma = np.sum(np.exp(gamma * ages))
    f2_gamma = np.sum(np.exp(2 * gamma * ages))
    g_gamma = np.sum(mu_values * np.exp(gamma * ages))
    m = np.sum(mu_values)

    alpha = ((m * f2_gamma) - (g_gamma * f1_gamma)) / ((N * f2_gamma) - (f1_gamma ** 2))
    beta = ((m * f1_gamma) - (N * g_gamma)) / ((f1_gamma ** 2 ) - (N * f2_gamma))

    return alpha, beta, gamma


def makeham_function(X_i, alpha, beta, gamma):
  mu_values = alpha + beta * np.exp(gamma * X_i)
  return mu_values

# Fit Makeham for men

7. 1st order payout and reserve

Calculate the guaranteed payout amount and project the 1st order reserve for the policy.

a) Determine the yearly payout amount, b.

Method:

  • Set contract inputs: current age (x), retirement age (z), payout length (s), time to retirement (u), guaranteed interest rate, initial reserve (G0), and annual premium.
  • Converted the guaranteed rate to a force of interest $(_g = ln(1 + rate))$ for continuous compounding.
  • Computed the present value of benefits by summing monthly payments from retirement to the end of the payout period, weighting each month by survival from age x and discounting at _g.
  • Computed the present value of premiums by summing monthly premiums from issue to retirement, also weighted by survival and discounted at _g.
  • Solved for the level yearly payout b by equaling the PV-payout function with the PV-premium function.
  • Evaluated survival probabilities using the previously fitted Makeham parameters (women) for consistency with earlier mortality estimations.
In[57]:

PV_payout = 0
for t in np.arange(12 * u + 1, 12 * (u + s) + 1):
    surv_ratio = survival(x + t/12, alpha_women, beta_women, gamma_women) / survival(x, alpha_women, beta_women, gamma_women)
    discount = np.exp(-delta_g * t/12)
    PV_payout = PV_payout + surv_ratio * discount

PV_premiums = 0
for t in np.arange(1, 12 * u + 1):
    surv_ratio = survival(x + t/12, alpha_women, beta_women, gamma_women) / survival(x, alpha_women, beta_women, gamma_women)
    discount = np.exp(-delta_g * t/12)
    PV_premiums = PV_premiums + surv_ratio * discount

b = float(12 * (G_0 + (premium / 12) * PV_premiums) / PV_payout)
